Let's write code to visualize and enhance the image to better inspect for abnormalities. ```python import matplotlib.pyplot as plt import numpy as np # Show the original image plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8)) plt.imshow(image_clue_0) plt.title("Original Fundus Image") plt.axis('off') plt.show() # Enhance contrast using histogram equalization (on each channel) def enhance_contrast(img): arr = np.asarray(img) enhanced = np.zeros_like(arr) for i in range(3): # For R, G, B channels channel = arr[..., i] hist, bins = np.histogram(channel.flatten(), 256, [0,256]) cdf = hist.cumsum() cdf_normalized = cdf * hist.max()/ cdf.max() cdf_m = np.ma.masked_equal(cdf, 0) cdf_m = (cdf_m - cdf_m.min())*255/(cdf_m.max()-cdf_m.min()) cdf = np.ma.filled(cdf_m,0).astype('uint8') enhanced[..., i] = cdf[channel] return enhanced enhanced_img = enhance_contrast(image_clue_0) plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8)) plt.imshow(enhanced_img) plt.title("Contrast Enhanced Fundus Image") plt.axis('off') plt.show() ```

- There are no abnormal peaks or distributions suggesting abnormal bright or dark regions (e.g., large hemorrhages or exudates).
